1. Template Literals ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Template literals use backticks (`) instead of single (') or double (") quotes.

Before ES6
let name = "Priya";

console.log("Hello " + name);

Output

Hello Priya
ES6 Template Literal
let name = "Priya";

console.log(`Hello ${name}`);

Output

Hello Priya

Notice:

Backticks: `
Variable inside ${}
String Interpolation ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Interpolation means inserting variables or expressions inside a string.

let firstName = "Priya";
let city = "Coimbatore";

console.log(`My name is ${firstName} and I live in ${city}.`);

Output

My name is Priya and I live in Coimbatore.
Expressions Inside ${}
let a = 10;
let b = 20;

console.log(`Sum = ${a + b}`);

Output

Sum = 30
Function Calls
function square(num) {
    return num * num;
}

console.log(`Square = ${square(5)}`);

Output

Square = 25
Multi-line Strings ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Before ES6:

let message = "Hello\n" +
              "Welcome\n" +
              "JavaScript";

With Template Literals:

let message = `
Hello
Welcome
JavaScript
`;

console.log(message);

Output

Hello
Welcome
JavaScript
Real-World Example
let product = "Laptop";
let price = 55000;

console.log(`Product: ${product}
Price: ₹${price}`);

Output

Product: Laptop
Price: ₹55000
2. Object Destructuring ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Extract object properties into variables.

let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27,
    city: "Coimbatore"
};

let { name, age, city } = student;

console.log(name);
console.log(age);
console.log(city);

Output

Priya
27
Coimbatore
Rename Variables
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

let {
    name: studentName,
    age: studentAge
} = student;

console.log(studentName);
console.log(studentAge);

Output

Priya
27
Default Values
let student = {
    name: "Priya"
};

let {
    name,
    city = "Chennai"
} = student;

console.log(city);

Output

Chennai
Nested Object Destructuring
let employee = {
    name: "Lokesh",
    address: {
        city: "Coimbatore",
        state: "Tamil Nadu"
    }
};

let {
    address: { city, state }
} = employee;

console.log(city);
console.log(state);

Output

Coimbatore
Tamil Nadu
3. Array Destructuring ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Extract values from an array.

let colors = ["Red", "Green", "Blue"];

let [first, second, third] = colors;

console.log(first);
console.log(second);
console.log(third);

Output

Red
Green
Blue
Skip Values
let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40];

let [first, , third] = numbers;

console.log(first);
console.log(third);

Output

10
30
Default Values
let numbers = [10];

let [a, b = 100] = numbers;

console.log(a);
console.log(b);

Output

10
100
Swap Variables ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Without a temporary variable:

let x = 10;
let y = 20;

[x, y] = [y, x];

console.log(x);
console.log(y);

Output

20
10
Destructuring Function Parameters
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

function display({ name, age }) {
    console.log(`${name} is ${age} years old.`);
}

display(student);

Output

Priya is 27 years old.
Real-World Example – API Response
const user = {
    id: 101,
    name: "Priya",
    email: "priya@example.com"
};

const { name, email } = user;

console.log(name);
console.log(email);

Output

Priya
priya@example.com
Common Mistakes
❌ Using Quotes in Destructuring

Wrong

let { "name" } = student;

Correct

let { name } = student;
❌ Forgetting Backticks

Wrong

console.log("Hello ${name}");

Output

Hello ${name}

Correct

console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
Interview Questions ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
1. What are Template Literals?

Template literals are strings enclosed in backticks (`) that support interpolation and multi-line strings.

2. What is String Interpolation?

It allows variables and expressions to be embedded inside strings using ${}.

Example:

let name = "Priya";

console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
3. What is Destructuring?

Destructuring extracts values from objects or arrays into variables.

4. Can you provide default values in destructuring?

Yes.

let { city = "Chennai" } = student;
